      <tr>
        <td rowspan="4" align="center" valign="middle" class="success"><strong>Session A:<br>Energy & Sustainablity</strong><br>Chair: Stylianos Varchanis (Flatiron Institute)</td> 
        <td>9:15 &ndash; 9:30 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Designing Flow Batteries for Long Duration Energy Storage</strong><br>
        Ioanna Itskou (MIT)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionAtalk1')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionAtalk1" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          As the human population and general standard of living continue to grow, so does the global demand for energy, especially in the form of electricity. In order to tackle our energy and sustainability goals, we are increasingly integrating renewable energy sources such as solar and wind; however, due to the intermittent nature of these sources, there is a need for long-term storing of the produced electricity to support the grid/data centers. Some of the most common energy storage methods include conventional (e.g., Li-ion) batteries, pumped-storage hydropower, and compressed air. These methods come with their own limitations linked to limited infrastructure availability, large capital costs, and material scarcity. As grid-scale storage demands capabilities such as scalability, low cost, and long lifetimes, flow batteries resurface as promising candidates. They offer reliability and scalability with decoupled energy/power, and years-long lifetimes with minimum maintenance. Flow batteries have limited energy density compared to conventional batteries, but they can potentially be more cost-effective for long duration energy storage, with the appropriate chemistry and engineering design. In the Brushett Group, we design and develop prototypes for robust flow battery systems at different scales, with chemistry based on cheap and universally abundant materials, applicable in real life.
        </div></td>
      </tr>

      <tr>
        <td>9:30 &ndash; 9:45 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Toward Intelligent Water Infrastructure: Multi-Modal Sensing for Continuous Network Monitoring</strong><br>
        Konstantinos Sitaropoulos (The University of Texas at Austin)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionAtalk2')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionAtalk2" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Continuous monitoring of water distribution networks (WDNs) remains a critical challenge due to diverse system failures, from slowly evolving leaks to sudden pipe bursts with significant economic and societal impacts. No single sensing modality can capture this full spectrum. This work synthesizes findings from two complementary projects leveraging IoT-enabled sensing for large-scale monitoring. In the first project, pressure sensor data from a large urban WDN in East Asia are analyzed to monitor system dynamics, detect transient events, and identify patterns through unsupervised learning. An adaptive denoising approach enhances real-time pressure analysis without suppressing critical events. While pressure sensing captures system-level dynamics and large events, its sensitivity to small, gradual leaks is limited. The second project addresses this gap by investigating acoustic leak detection using sensors deployed in an operational WDN in the US, complemented by laboratory datasets capturing diverse layouts, leak types, and conditions. Spectral and time–frequency analyses are integrated with interpretable machine learning to identify leak-induced acoustic signatures and reveal meaningful frequency bands. In parallel, multi-scale statistical methods capture signal complexity for robust detection under variable conditions. Together, these approaches demonstrate the potential of multi-modal IoT sensing for continuous monitoring and proactive water infrastructure management.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>9:45 &ndash; 10:00 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Assessing the Financial Feasibility of Agrivoltaics in New Hampshire</strong><br>
        Eleftheria Malesiada (University of New Hampshire)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionAtalk3')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionAtalk3" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Agrivoltaics is an emerging innovation that mitigates competition between agriculture and energy generation by co-locating solar photovoltaics and crop cultivation. This approach offers plethora of benefits for agricultural systems, including enhanced water efficiency, potential impacts on crop yields, expanded renewable energy generation, and increased farm revenues. Together, these attributes position agrivoltaics as a promising pathway toward integrated food-energy-climate solutions.
          Consistent with national trends, solar photovoltaics are gaining momentum as a strategic component within New Hampshire’s electricity system. Yet, agrivoltaics activity in the state remains virtually nonexistent due to perceived economic, policy, and technical barriers, compounded by substantial knowledge gaps among critical stakeholders. This research addresses these gaps by synthesizing stakeholder-identified weaknesses at the energy-agriculture interface and developing a dynamic optimization model to asses the long-term financial sustainability of USDA incentive funding for agrivoltaics adoption, while evaluating farm-level profitability. Framed within the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals, the study highlights agrivoltaics’ contributions to SDG 2 (Zero Hunger), SDG 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), SDG 10 (Reduced Inequalities), and SDG 13 (Climate Action), offering actionable insights for equitable and scalable agrivoltaics deployment.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>10:00 &ndash; 10:15 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Data Centers and Energy Poverty in the United States: Assessing Distributional Implications of Rapid Load Growth in the Artificial Intelligence Era</strong><br>
        Constantine Spandagos (University of New Hampshire)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionAtalk4')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionAtalk4" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Accelerated by the current surge in artificial intelligence applications, cloud computing, and digital services, the expansion of data centers is now a significant driver of electricity demand growth. Today, almost half of the global data center demand occurs in the United States, where concerns exist about potential implications for energy poverty. The latter is defined as the inability of households to meet their energy needs—a multidimensional phenomenon currently affecting one-third of United States households. The emergence of large data centers introduces new system dynamics that may impact energy-burdened households in ways that have not yet been systematically examined. To address this gap, this research identifies, for the first time, five mechanisms linking rapid data center load growth to energy-poverty risks. These mechanisms concern: electricity prices and cost allocation; grid congestion and reliability; competition for clean energy resources; localized environmental and health impacts; and water stress. Evidence indicates that baseline energy burdens are uneven and can be further impacted by rate increases, power outages, and environmental stressors for vulnerable households. To mitigate these impacts, policy reforms need to focus on new interconnection standards, fair cost recovery principles, and modern environmental reporting approaches. Near-term outcomes will depend on implementation, transparency, monitoring, and adaptation, as conditions evolve.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      
      

