      <tr>
        <td rowspan="4" align="center" valign="middle" class="success"><strong>Session B:<br>Cancer Research & Translational Medicine</strong><br>Chair: Ioannis Sanidas (Harvard University)</td>
        <td>10:15 &ndash; 10:30 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Refining Prostate Cancer Risk Stratification Through Hierarchical Machine Learning for Grade Group Prediction</strong><br>
        Lampros Pantazis (Massachusetts General Hospital, Harvard University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionBtalk1')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionBtalk1" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Prostate cancer aggressiveness is assessed by Gleason Grading (GG 1-5), yet biopsy misclassification compared to surgical findings remains significant. To address this limitation, we developed machine learning (ML) models to predict the true GG at radical prostatectomy (RP).
          Patients who underwent RP were identified in our institutional prostate biopsy database and split into training and test sets (75/25%). A two-stage hierarchical approach was developed with the first model predicting GG1, GG2-3, GG4-5, and the second distinguishing GG2, 3. Feature were selected among the available demographic, clinical, and pathology variables. Various ML models were trained and compared for each stage. Performance was evaluated on the test set and compared with biopsy GG and NCCN Risk Group. The primary performance metric was the quadratic weighted kappa (QWK). 
          Among 535 identified patients, 82 (15.3%) had GG1, 283 (52.9%) GG2, 85 (15.9%) GG3, and 85 (15.9%) GG4-5 at RP and biopsy misclassification rate was 41.3%. The best performance was achieved by the Ordinal Forest-Random Forest combination with a QWK of 0.77 (95%CI:0.67-0.85). The ML approach significantly outperformed NCCN Risk Group (QWK=0.603(0.48-0.715), p<0.001) and biopsy GG (QWK=0.646(0.51-0.757), p=0.0016).
          Our model outperformed clinical approaches in forecasting prostate cancer GG at RP, highlighting its potential to improve risk stratification. Further validation in larger cohorts is warranted to confirm these results.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>10:30 &ndash; 10:45 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Pan-Cancer Neutrophil States and Their Protumor Implications</strong><br>
        Evangelia Bolli (Broad Institute, Massachusetts General Hospital, Harvard University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionBtalk2')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionBtalk2" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Tumor-associated neutrophils (TANs) are abundant across cancers, yet their phenotypic diversity and functional states remain poorly defined. Here, we introduce a cell-type probability classifier that recovers low-transcript neutrophils from scRNAseq datasets, enabling pan-cancer analyses of TAN heterogeneity. Across >190 human and murine tumors, we identify a conserved differentiation trajectory that culminates in a terminal CCL3 hi state. This state exhibits pro-tumor transcriptional programs, including those involved in hypoxic adaptation and senescence. Consistently, CCL3 hi TANs are enriched in hypoxic tumor niches in both humans and mice. Through mechanistic perturbations of neutrophil-derived CCL3 in mice, we show that it sustains TAN survival in hypoxic tumor regions via CCR1-dependent signaling. These findings establish CCL3 as a conserved marker and functional driver of pro-tumor neutrophils in growing tumors, and provide a scalable
          framework for dissecting neutrophil biology across cancer types.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>11:15 &ndash; 11:30 AM</td>
        <td><strong>IL-4/13 Signaling Blockade Increases Breast Cancer Risk</strong><br>
        Stergiani Telliou (Massachusetts General Hospital)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionBtalk3')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionBtalk3" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Type 2 cytokines, interleukin-4 (IL-4) and IL-13, play a critical role in driving allergic inflammation. However, their contribution to tissue homeostasis and disease prevention remains poorly understood. Herein, we demonstrate that IL-4/IL-13 signaling in breast epithelial cells prevents breast cancer development by promoting their differentiation. Utilizing mouse models of spontaneous breast carcinogenesis, we discovered that loss of IL-4 receptor alpha (IL-4Rα) or IL-13 markedly accelerated breast tumor development in an immune cell-independent manner. Importantly, exposure of the mammary epithelial cells to IL-4 and/or IL-13 induced their differentiation in vitro. Mammary epithelial cells exposed to IL-4 and IL-13 showed reduced ability for oncogene-induced transformation in vivo. IL-4Rα was highly expressed in the luminal progenitor compartment of mouse mammary glands, and the loss of IL-4Rα led to an expansion of luminal progenitors as the cell of origin for breast cancer. Luminal progenitor cells substantially expressed IL-4Rα in the human breast glands, which was significantly decreased during aging and cancer development. Collectively, our findings underscore a critical physiological function for type 2 cytokines in driving breast epithelial cell differentiation, revealing a novel non-immune function of cytokines in tissue homeostasis and cancer prevention.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>11:30 &ndash; 11:45 AM</td>
        <td><strong>Combination Controlled Drug Delivery and Photothermal Ablation for Breast Tumors and Bone Metastases</strong><br>
        Litsa Kapsalis (MIT)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionBtalk4')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionBtalk4" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Around 65-75% of advanced breast cancer patients experience bone metastases. These patients’ tumor-mediated bone degradation results in painful pathological fractures, which significantly impact quality of life and reduce their treatment options for tumor removal. In the current standard of care (SOC), minimally invasive approaches for tumor treatment are limited, and drugs facilitating bone generation are poorly targeted to metastatic lesions. Thus, there is a need for treatment regimens suited for patients with the highest fracture risk via safer ablation and adaptive dosing of bone-generating drugs. 
          Here, we develop a combination photothermal ablation (PTT) and controlled release microparticle drug depot treatment. We integrate 665 nm red light laser ablation (less destructive than current SOC) with heat-responsive, controlled drug release. First, we treat mammary tumors with PTT + controlled-release chemo, and then show proof of concept for use in a bone metastasis model with bone-regenerative drugs. 
          We fabricated particles, characterized drug release at ablative and physiologic temperatures, and demonstrated biological activity of SOC drugs within particles. Moreover, we show in vitro that PTT may induce immunogenic apoptosis and, when combined with drug-loaded particles, slows tumor growth in vivo in a mammary tumor model. Particles can facilitate local delivery when in contact with bone, positioning the system for intraosseous utility in a bone metastasis model.
        </div></td>
      </tr>

