      <tr>
        <td rowspan="4" align="center" valign="middle" class="success"><strong>Session C:<br>Machine Learning & Neural Networks</strong><br>Chair: Markos Markakis (MIT) </td>
        <td>1:30 &ndash; 1:45 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Interpretable Machine-Learning-Based Predictive Modeling for mRNA-Loaded Lipid Nanoparticle Formulation</strong><br>
        Konstantinos Zinelis (MIT)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionCtalk1')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionCtalk1" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Lipid nanoparticles (LNPs) are the leading platform for mRNA delivery, where critical quality attributes such as particle size and morphology depend on complex interactions between formulation composition and process conditions. Mechanistic population balance equation (PBE) models capture nucleation, growth, and coalescence but often miss formulation-specific and scale-dependent effects, while purely data-driven models lack interpretability.

          We develop an interpretable machine-learning framework for predictive modeling of LNP formulation using Smart Process Analytics and sparse, structure-constrained learning. Using datasets from impinging jet mixing and microfluidic systems, we model mean particle size and morphology descriptors, including bleb fraction, as functions of formulation and process variables. The models identify buffer concentration and residence time as dominant drivers, capturing nonlinear and scale-specific behavior. A hybrid extension incorporates data-driven corrections to mechanistic predictions, improving accuracy while preserving physical insight. 

          This framework enables design-space exploration, formulation optimization, and scalable, interpretable LNP development.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>1:45 &ndash; 2:00 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Giza: Tackling the Deployability Crisis in ML-for-Systems using Predictor Hierarchies</strong><br>
        Christos Zarkos (MIT)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionCtalk2')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionCtalk2" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          The systems community has increasingly turned to machine learning (ML) to manage the growing complexity of software and hardware stacks. Despite promising results, the integration of ML in systems is limited by the lack of interpretability, generalizability, and low control latency. Prior work typically optimizes for only one or two of these properties, failing to provide a holistic solution to enable reliable deployment. To optimize all three properties, this work proposes Giza, a methodology for organizing ML predictors into hierarchies that utilize uncertainty-based fallback logic. Giza leverages a model's uncertainty as a real-time proxy for its accuracy, routing inputs through a multi-level hierarchy that combines a fast, interpretable surrogate model with an opaque but accurate base neural network to obtain the best of both. We evaluate Giza across three diverse systems tasks: cluster resource management, adaptive bitrate selection, and storage I/O admission control. Across all tasks, Giza matches or exceeds the generalizability of complex base models while achieving a speedup of 3-200x in the prediction latency. Furthermore, 29% to 100% of decisions are handled by the interpretable surrogate, providing the transparency required for system debugging and auditing.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>2:00 &ndash; 2:15 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Emotional Conditioning, Intentionality, and Self-Awareness in Adaptive Autonomous Systems</strong><br>
        Pandelis Kriadis (University of York & Cerence AI)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionCtalk3')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionCtalk3" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          As autonomous systems increasingly operate in open, real-world environments, their effectiveness depends not only on performance, but on exhibiting intentionality, self-awareness, and context-sensitive behaviour. In prior REBA work, this challenge is framed through Kantian autonomy, where intentional behaviour emerges from self-aware internal states that guide action, rather than purely reactive responses. Drawing on the Cannon–Bard theory of emotion, emotional processes are understood as parallel drivers that directly shape action and awareness. This paper introduces AREBA, a neurocomputational framework that embeds emotional conditioning into system dynamics to support intentional, self-regulating behaviour. By extending the leaky integrate-and-fire model with adaptive excitatory and inhibitory gain modulation, AREBA enables experience-driven adaptation through mechanisms analogous to habituation and sensitisation. Crucially, this adaptation remains bounded by explicit constraints, preserving safety and interpretability while advancing a principled path toward autonomous systems that are intentional, self-aware, and trustworthy.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>2:15 &ndash; 2:30 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Fourier Neural Operators for Fast Estimation of Hodgkin-Huxley Neuron Model</strong><br>
        Alexandros Kerwick (Northeastern University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionCtalk4')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionCtalk4" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          The Hodgkin-Huxley model uses stiff, nonlinear ordinary differential equations (ODEs) to describe neuron action potential initiation and propagation in response to injected current waveforms. Stiff ODEs are computationally expensive due to the high resolution needed to capture fast-changing dynamics. Efficient solutions are therefore needed for large-scale simulations. Data-driven methods have become a popular alternative to conventional numerical solvers, offering reduced computational cost at high temporal or spatial resolutions. Neural Operators offer a novel approach to approximate families of differential equations. Unlike traditional Neural Networks which learn a function mapping input to output data, Neural Operators encode input and output features separately to learn an operator mapping input to output functions. This method yields the unique guarantee of both discretization invariance and universal approximation. In this paper, we use a Fourier Neural Operator (FNO) to approximate the Hodgkin-Huxley model of neuron dynamics. We stimulate the neuron with a wide variety of injected current waveforms and assess the Neural Operator's ability to predict action potentials and subthreshold responses. The FNO successfully predicts stimulation responses across multiple behavioral states with low inference times. Its accuracy and efficiency over a wide parameter space demonstrate utility for modeling stiff dynamical systems.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      

