      <tr>
        <td rowspan="4" align="center" valign="middle" class="success"><strong>Session D:<br>Biomedical Sciences</strong><br>Chair: Ioannis Lempesis (Harvard University)</td>
        <td>3:00 &ndash; 3:15 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Functional Mapping of Noncoding Multiple Sclerosis Risk Variants Across Human Immune Cell Models Using MPRA</strong><br>
        Elisavet Kapetanou (Yale University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionDtalk1')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionDtalk1" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Most multiple sclerosis (MS) and autoimmune disease risk variants map to noncoding regions of the genome, yet the mechanisms by which they contribute to disease remain poorly defined. To address this challenge, we integrated genetic prioritization with massively parallel reporter assays (MPRAs) to systematically assess regulatory effects of MS-associated variants across multiple immune cell types and activation state contexts. An MS-focused MPRA library was designed comprising prioritized variants from GWAS fine-mapped susceptibility loci and tested allele-specific regulatory activity in Jurkat, THP-1, and K562 cells under distinct activation states. This cross-context analysis identified expression-modulating variants (emVars) and revealed cell-type-dependent regulatory effects. Integration of MPRA results with epigenomic annotations and fine-mapping evidence further allowed prioritization of candidate causal variants, regulatory elements, and downstream target genes. To elucidate further the role of the variants identified through the MPRA assay and probe their underlying mechanisms, we are introducing these SNPs to various immune cell types utilizing base editors delivered via viral-like particles (VLPs). Together, these methods provide a systematic functional framework for interpreting MS risk loci and narrowing the set of variants most likely to mediate disease-associated effects in a cell type and context-dependent manner.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>3:15 &ndash; 3:30 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Structural and Biomechanical Basis of Pacinian Vibration Tuning</strong><br>
        Zoe Sarafis (Harvard University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionDtalk2')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionDtalk2" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Our sense of touch allows us to perceive our environment, socially interact, and guides movement. Specialized neurons called mechanoreceptors detect different sensations. Pacinian neurons have a unique ability to detect high-frequency mechanical vibrations. This ability arises from the Pacinian corpuscle, a deep tissue structure at the Pacinian nerve terminal, consisting of a central axon surrounded by concentric lamellar cells. Little is known on how vibration is transmitted from the skin to nervous system. Pacinian neurons also exhibit diverse vibration tuning and sensitivities, responding to specific ranges of frequencies and forces. It remains unclear how the corpuscle enables exquisite vibration tuning, and whether tuning depends on corpuscle shape, size, and location. Using mouse genetic tools, in vivo electrophysiology, and tissue clearing, we measured the relationship between the structure and location of Pacinian corpuscles and their functional tuning in the limbs and digits. We found anatomically organized heterogeneity in corpuscle and axonal structure within and across body regions. We observed that corpuscle location and structure account for variance in Pacinian vibration tuning. Lastly, we found that tissue biomechanics determine Pacinian neuron firing. These findings suggest that corpuscle structure, location, and tissue mechanics shape sensory neuron tuning, and can provide sources of variance enabling population coding of mechanical vibration stimuli.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>3:30 &ndash; 3:45 PM</td>
        <td><strong>A Human Metabolic Reaction Network Meta-Database for Consistent Comparison of Genome-Scale Metabolic Models and Multi-Omic Integration</strong><br>
        Marilena Pantziri (FORTH/ICE-HT, University of Patras)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionDtalk3')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionDtalk3" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Background: Genome-scale metabolic network models (GEMs) are widely used in metabolic engineering and systems biology to analyze metabolic pathways. Human GEMs support studies of metabolic flux rewiring and applications in disease diagnosis and therapy design. However, the increasing number of models in different formats and repositories creates challenges in interoperability, comparison, and consistent updating with genome annotations, limiting standardized workflows and multi-omics integration.
          <br>
          Methods: We developed a standardized meta-database of the human metabolic reactome by integrating data from ExplorEnz, UniProt, Rhea, and ChEBI within a relational MySQL framework.
          <br>
          Results: The database includes three core tables (Enzymes, Reactions, Metabolites) and their connections, extended to the reviewed human proteome, transcriptome, and genome. It enables direct model comparison, identification of missing pathways, and detection of inconsistencies between metabolic networks and genomic annotations.
          <br>
          Conclusions: This framework supports integration of metabolomic, proteomic, transcriptomic, and genomic data, improving metabolic reconstruction and flux analysis workflows, and can be extended to other organisms.
        </div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>3:45 &ndash; 4:00 PM</td>
        <td><strong>Epigenetic Silencing of HBV cccDNA: Role of Linker Histone H1-0 in Host Restriction and Viral Evasion</strong><br>
        Georgios Dangas (Emory University)<br>
        <a href="javascript: toggleVisibility ('#sessionDtalk4')">Toggle Abstract</a>
        <div id="sessionDtalk4" class="abstract" style="display: none;">
          Chronic hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection affects >300 million people worldwide and remains incurable due to the persistence of cccDNA, a nuclear episome that serves as the template for all viral RNAs. A cure is rarely achieved with current therapies. While nucleos(t)ide analogs effectively suppress viral replication, they fail to eliminate or silence cccDNA. Interferon-α (IFNα) remains the only approved therapy capable of achieving a cure; however, it is effective in only 10% of patients. Importantly, its efficacy suggests that hepatocytes possess intrinsic mechanisms to silence cccDNA. To identify host factors underlying IFN-mediated control of HBV, we performed proteomic profiling in human hepatocytes. Comparative analysis of IFNα-treated HBV-infected and uninfected hepatocytes identified 42 proteins induced by IFNα in uninfected cells but selectively suppressed during HBV infection, indicating viral antagonism of antiviral pathways. Among those, we identified the histone H1-0 as a previously unrecognized HBV restriction factor. CRISPR-mediated knockout and overexpression studies demonstrated that loss of H1-0 enhances HBV transcription, whereas increased H1-0 expression suppresses viral transcription. Western blot analyses further showed reduced H1-0 protein levels in HBV-infected hepatocytes. Together, these findings establish H1-0 as the first histone with antiviral activity against HBV and reveal a chromatin-based host-virus conflict that regulates viral persistence.
        </div></td>
      </tr>

